  "text": "Melanoma spheroids were prepared using the liquid overlay method. Briefly, 200 L of melanoma cells (25,000/mL) were added to a 96-well plate coated with 1.5% agar (Difco, Sparks, MD, USA). Plates were incubated for 72 h, by which time cells had organized into 3D spheroids. Spheroids were then harvested and implanted into a bovine collagen I gel containing EMEM, L-glutamine, and 2% fetal bovine serum. Normal 2% melanoma medium was overlaid on top of the solidified collagen. Spheroids were treated with 5.0 M of 2ME for 5 days. Spheroids were then washed twice in PBS before being treated with calcein-AM and ethidium bromide (Molecular Probes, Eugene, OR, USA) for 1 h at 37 • C according to the manufacturer's instructions. After this time, pictures of the invading spheroids were taken using a Nikon-300 inverted fluorescence microscope. Calcein and ethidium bromide staining were used as a live/dead cell marker, respectively. The images were imported to Definiens Tissue Studio v4.1 software to analyze the fluorescence as described by [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and the ratio was determined by live fluorescence divided by dead fluorescence.",
